  "prompt": "Why do birth control pills contain acetaminophen?",
  "response": "Birth control pills typically do not contain acetaminophen. Birth control pills primarily contain synthetic hormones, such as estrogen and progestin, which are used to prevent ovulation, regulate menstrual cycles, and provide contraceptive effects. \n\nHowever, some pill formulations may have specific combinations with other medications for particular medical conditions. In certain contexts, acetaminophen might be included in a combined contraceptive and pain relief medication, but this is not standard for all birth control pills. If you have a specific formulation in mind or if there's a new type of combination product that includes acetaminophen, please provide more details for further clarification. Otherwise, for most traditional birth control pills, acetaminophen is not an ingredient.",
